{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641178"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:24:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:24:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17866"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17866"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10580"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72659"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10580"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17866"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58129"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"10083"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24664"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24667"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72659"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct regarding the hormones involved in fatty acid oxidation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Insulin activates protein phosphatase 2A (PP2A)","Insulin increases the activity of carnitine palmitoyltransferase I (CPT I)","Glucagon increases the activity of acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC)","Glucagon decreases the activity of carnitine palmitoyltransferase I (CPT I)","Insulin decreases the activity of hormone-sensitive lipase"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin activates protein phosphatase 2A (PP2A)\u003C/strong\u003E, which is involved in the dephosphorylation and inactivation of acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC). This reduces the conversion of acetyl-CoA to malonyl-CoA, thereby decreasing fatty acid synthesis and promoting fatty acid oxidation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucagon increases the activity of acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC)\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Glucagon actually decreases ACC activity, promoting fatty acid oxidation by reducing malonyl-CoA levels, which relieves inhibition on carnitine palmitoyltransferase I (CPT I).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin decreases the activity of hormone-sensitive lipase\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Insulin actually inhibits hormone-sensitive lipase, reducing lipolysis and free fatty acid availability for oxidation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucagon decreases the activity of carnitine palmitoyltransferase I (CPT I)\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Glucagon promotes fatty acid oxidation by decreasing malonyl-CoA levels, which increases CPT I activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin increases the activity of carnitine palmitoyltransferase I (CPT I)\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Insulin increases malonyl-CoA levels, which inhibits CPT I, reducing fatty acid oxidation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Insulin activates protein phosphatase 2A (PP2A), which plays a role in the regulation of fatty acid metabolism.","Protein phosphatase 2A (PP2A) decreases the activity of acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC), reducing fatty acid synthesis."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: PMC8411952","Wakil SJ, Abu-Elheiga LA. Fatty acid metabolism: target for metabolic syndrome. J Lipid Res. 2009 Apr;50 Suppl(Suppl):S138-43. doi: 10.1194/jlr.R800079-JLR200. Epub 2008 Dec 1. PMID: 19047759; PMCID: PMC2674721"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58129"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17866"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58129"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T05:34:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T05:35:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10580"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72659"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.